## Loomings

To provide him with a generous head start,
we imagine our hiker to be responsible.
He is hiking as early in the year as he can manage:
in early June, rather than the furnace months of July or August.
He is careful to catch the early Hikers’ Express shuttle, not the late,
?am.

We grant our hiker generous knowledge
Several times Plateau Point layers

As this is the hiker’s first descent of the South Kaibab,
he is buoyed by perpetual pleasant surprise
at how rapidly dispatches layers
compared to bright angel
A series of swift switchbacks
soon deliver him to the Coconino Cliffs and ooah point,
then a long unbroken diagonal brings him to the top of the Redwall.
At the bottom Tonto Platform and the Tip Off.

The South Kaibab strikes our hiker
as not only a more expansive trail than the Bright Angel —
open to vast views to one or both sides,
instead of always crawling along one side of a valley
with a view of the other —
but as more
There seem to be fewer tourists (especially at this hour)
and a larger proportion of serious hikers:
Park materials warn tourists away from the SKT
since it offers no water,
and its trailhead is at the end of a shuttle ride
instead of sitting in Grand Canyon village itself.

Perhaps making as much as three miles per hour downhill,
the hiker can reach the Tonto Platform and the Tip Off
within the first two hours of the hike,
which already puts most of the familiar layers of the Canyon
behind him.
Only a few minutes more
and he is descending into the Tapeats,
the final
before he passes the Great Unconformity
and descends the ancient granites and schists
that wall the Colorado River itself.
While, yes, the NKT north of the River will be twice the length
of the South Kaibab along which he has descended,
the hiker feels justified in concluding that — geologically —
the hike is nearly half over.

Alas!

Giddy with the early morning
as he breaches the Tapeats
and descends towards the River,
all the hiker sees are the simple and schematic rocks across the river:
the corrugated Tapeats capping the gray and pink swirls
of the basement rocks
whose cliffs angle sharply down into Upper Granite Gorge.

PIC of hakatai

In awe at the view,
in a hurry to reach the River,
eyes at huh the mighty monuments to the north,
the hiker does not stop to ponder a puzzle:
what, exactly, is the loose red layer they’re actually standing on?
The hiker fails to see beneath his own feet,
for there a mystery lies.
If, as BAT geology has taught him to expect,
the Tapeats everywhere overlies the basement rocks,
then why is the SKT making lazily swoops
across a loose red sandstone
with no analog along the more familiar BAT?

PIC

This is the first inkling
that the Canyon’s geology will not nearly as simple
as the hiker expects.

This loose red sandstone, as it happens, is named the Hakatai Shale.
When the hiker’s feet encounter it next,
it will be in a wide desert valley of baking sunlight,
shimmering haze, and little shade.

The SKT troubles him with the incongruity its incongruousness
for what seems like only a few moments.
Soon enough his feet is on basement rock,
and the final switchbacks as he approaches the tunnel and Black Bridge
are carved into the ancient granite and schist of the basement.

But though the hiker has ignored it,
the Canyon has now issued its warning.
The hiker, plunging on heedless,
reaches the River in record time,
stops for a photo on the famous Black Bridge,
then refills his water at the spigots an actual sink
beneath beautiful trees of the Bright Angel Campground.

Now, it’s time to make the trip back uphill.

